<paragraph id="8BD0CA0BFFD2FFA50E5C4A03643575AA" blockId="7.[813,1420,310,698]" box="[850,1287,369,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="B91B1619FFD2FFA50E5C4A03650375AA" bold="true" box="[850,1073,369,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">Material examined.</emphasis>
<tableCitation id="C6EDFFB0FFD2FFA509334A0365BF75AA" box="[1085,1165,369,393]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="3.[166,218,517,537]" captionText="Table 1. Species, IUCN status, number of individuals sampled per site in Pelus River, and data available from previous studies in Perak River. LC: least concern; NE: not evaluated; DD: data deficient; NT: nearly threatened; *: mean index; U: upper; M: middle; L: lower portion of Pelus River; UPMZM: Universiti Putra Malaysia Zoology Museum." pageId="7" pageNumber="322">Table 1</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="1354D68EFFD2FFA509944A03643175AA" box="[1178,1283,369,393]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[168,230,1057,1077]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,160,1028]" captionTargetId="figure-438@6.[168,1421,160,1028]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Species sampling in this study: a) Channa gachua (UPMZM F 1049, 94.6 mm TL); b) Batasio fluviatilis (UPMZM F 1057, 77.3 mm TL); c) Leiocassis poecilopterus (UPMZM F 1061, 78.0 mm TL); d) Mystus cavasius (UPMZM F 1065, 110.0 mm TL); e) Clarias leiacanthus (UPMZM F 1067, 137.2 mm TL); f) Glyptothorax major (UPMZM F 1071, 60.2 mm TL); g) Glyptothorax siamensis (UPMZM F 1076, 71.2 mm TL); h) Macrognathus keithi (UPMZM F 1080, 117.0 mm TL)." pageId="7" pageNumber="322">Figure 4e</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD0CA0BFFD2FFA50E5C4AE1629F7699" blockId="7.[813,1420,310,698]" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">
This species can be distinguished from congeners that occur in this region by a combination of features: smooth pectoral-fin spine, 68–78 dorsal-fin rays, 58–64 anal-fin rays, moderately broad supraoccipital process, and a distinct color pattern of white spots on the sides of the body. This species is common in forested, more pristine habitats than the sympatric 
<taxonomicName id="4C6FB188FFD2FFA50952492C65DB7655" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1116,1257,606,630]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clariidae" genus="Clarias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="batrachus">
<emphasis id="B91B1619FFD2FFA50952492C65DB7655" box="[1116,1257,606,630]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">C. batrachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is usu- ally common in more open, disturbed habitats (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFEB7FAFFD2FFA5083549F262937699" author="Ambak MA &amp; Isa MM &amp; Zakaria MZ &amp; Ghaffar MA" pageId="7" pageNumber="322" refId="ref6880" refString="Ambak MA, Isa MM, Zakaria MZ, Ghaffar MA (2010) Fishes of Malaysia. Penerbit UMT, Universiti Malaysia Terengganu, Tereng- ganu, 334 pp." type="book" year="2010">Ambak et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
